ial lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1","Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade 2","Human papillomavirus effect","Koilocytic atypia","Reactive changes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Bethesda System classifies cervical cytology findings into several categories:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1\u003C/strong\u003E (CIN 1) is classified as a low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade 2\u003C/strong\u003E (CIN 2) is classified as HSIL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papillomavirus effect\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ekoilocytic atypia\u003C/strong\u003E are both features of LSIL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive changes\u003C/strong\u003E are considered benign findings\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHSIL includes CIN 2 and CIN 3/carcinoma in situ. These lesions have a higher risk of progression to invasive cancer and require closer surveillance or treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["High-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) includes CIN 2 and CIN 3/carcinoma in situ","Low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL) includes HPV changes and CIN 1","The Bethesda System standardises cervical cytology reporting internationally"],"references":["Pangarkar MA. The Bethesda System for reporting cervical cytology. Cytojournal. 2022 Apr 30;19:28. doi: 10.25259/CMAS_03_07_2021. PMID: 35673697; PMCID: PMC9168399.","Bal MS, Goyal R, Suri AK, Mohi MK. Detection of abnormal cervical cytology in Papanicolaou smears. J Cytol. 2012 Jan;29(1):45-7. doi: 10.4103/0970-9371.93222. PMID: 22438616; PMCID: PMC3307451.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstet